<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-080-264  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 080 264.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Patricia Seybold's Unix in the Office  Jan 1990 v5 n1 p20(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Seybold Office Computing Inc 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NetWare comes to Unix. (in NCR's Tower processors)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brown, Laure.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   NCR Corp. (products)Novell Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    NCR; NOVL.andO;Product:   NetWare ACS (Communications software) (usage)NCR Tower 32-200 (Microcomputer) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     UNIXAdaptabilitySoftwareConnectivityNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NetWare Comes to Unix The success of Unix hangs on a number ofvariables--among them, coexisting and enhancing the computer configurationsalready in place in most corporations.andP;  In recognizing this, NCR has takenadvantage of Novell's prominent position in the world of PC LANs andimplemented portable NetWare for its Tower series of Unix processors.andM;FEATURES.andP;  NCR's adaptation of NetWare enables Tower processors to becomeservers in a client/server architecture.andP;  The product offers most standardNetWare features, including:andM;* Transparent file storage and sharing.andP;  DOS, OS/2, and Macintosh users canstore files on the Tower NetWare server in a separate directory area.andO;Although they're stored as Unix files, they're accessible through nativenaming conventions.andM;* Host printer sharing.andM;* Security (combining NetWare security with Unix security where appropriate).andM;* Resources management and diagnostics.andM;New features include terminal emulation for DOS users and a system consolethat performs administrative functions such as displaying and modifyingserver information and backing up the file server.andM;COMPATIBILITY AND INTEROPERABILITY.andP;  A Tower NetWare server is compatiblewith existing NetWare clients.andP;  Through bridges, the Tower supportsToken-Ring, ARCNet, and Apple Talk, as well as TCP/IP and Ethernet-basedNetWare environments.andM;ISV SUPPORT.andP;  A number of ISVs plan to take advantage of the Tower's serverrole in a NetWare environment and are porting their software accordingly.andO;Database vendors see it as a vehicle for enhancing their distributed-databaseschemes.andP;  Oracle has announced limited release this month, with generalrelease later this quarter.andP;  Informix and Ingres announced plans for supportsas well.andP;  Other vendors, such as Uniplex, Access Technologies, andWordPerfect have also announced plans for support.andP;  And Cheyenne Software, anetwork management software vendor, plans to have Tower NetWare productsavailable this month.andM;NETWARE AND DCE.andP;  While it might not make such of a difference to NCR, astaunch member of Unix International, most companies who are interested indistributed computing are watching the results of OSF's request fortechnology for Distributed Computing Environment (DCE) very carefully.andO;NetWare, as well as PC-NFS, is a possible solution to the integration of PCsand PC LANs into DCE.andP;  However, it appears that LM/X (LAN Manager for Unix,or &quot;portable&quot; LAN Manager), which has the powerful support of IBM, Digital,Hewlett-Packard, Microsoft, and others (including ATandamp;T, which, though notformally supporting the submission, is an LM/X OEM), is likely to be chosenas the integration standard.andP;  Where this would leave NetWare, with itstremendous installed base, is unclear.andM;CONCLUSION.andP;  For NCR, it's a practical move; there's a lot to be gained inproviding the multiuser, multiprocessing functionality of Unix as a serverfor PC clients.andP;  Although the Tower series isn't exactly on the cutting edgeof hardware technology, Novell is tickled about the whole thing nonetheless.andO;Tower NetWare strengthens its reputation as a vendor of open networkcomputing solutions.andP;  Furthermore, it may just open up a whole new avenue forNovell--Unix.andO;</TEXT></DOC>